<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
The @HI{{masu}} stem, @Vmasustem{{}}, of almost any verb (except Sino-Japanese @HI{{suru}} verbs) can be used as a noun.
Some of these stems are treated as real nouns and appear as separate entries in dictionaries.
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{end}}:o}}warigayokereba,@FG{{@KJ{{whole^body}}:zentai}}gayokunara.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      If the end is alright, all becomes good.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Some verb stems can form compounds of the form @Vmasustem{{}}@Vmasustem{{}}. In this case the two stems have a contrastive meaning.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{o@FG{{@KJ{{gold}}:kane}}no@EM{{@FG{{@KJ{{lend}}:ka}}shi@FG{{@KJ{{borrow}}:ka}}ri}}hashinai@FG{{@KJ{{direction}}:hou}}gaii.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It is better not to borrow or lend money. (<em>Neither a lender nor a borrower be.</em>)
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
A few @Vmasustem{{}} nouns cannot be used as nouns in isolation but can be used in a compound.

<ul>
<table border=0>
<tr> <td> @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{thing}}:mono}}@FG{{@KJ{{know}}:shi}}ri}}     </td> <td> an erudite person       </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> @HI{{sozoro@FG{{@KJ{{walk}}:aru}}ki}}                       </td> <td> slow walking            </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{dog}}:inu}}@FG{{@KJ{{death}}:ji}}ni}}        </td> <td> die in vain             </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{flower}}:hana}}@FG{{@KJ{{see}}:mi}}}}        </td> <td> cherry blossom viewing  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

